¶ ⦊
  ‖ \ssection{Why} ⦉

  ‖ We can define algebraic operations on the points in $𝗥^n$
  which have geometric interpretations.⦉
⦉

¶ ⦊
  ‖ \ssection{Result} ⦉

  ‖ For $x, y ∈ 𝗥^n$, define $x + y$ by
    ◇ ⦊
      ‖ (x_1 +y_1, …, x_n + y_n) ⦉
    ⦉
    and for $α ∈ 𝗥$, define $α \cdot x$
    ◇ ⦊
      ‖ (α x_1, …, α x_n). ⦉
    ⦉⦉
⦉

¶ ⦊
  ‖ \begin{proposition} ⦉

  ‖ $𝗥^n$ is a vector space of dimension $n$ over $𝗥$ with $+$
    and $\cdot$. ⦉

  ‖ \end{proposition} ⦉
⦉

¶ ⦊
  ‖ For this reason, we call elements of $𝗥^n$ ❬(real) vectors❭. ⦉
⦉

